WEBVTT

00:00:00.200 --> 00:00:03.440
So if you'll allow me to complain a little bit,

00:00:03.440 --> 00:00:07.440
if there's one question that I have hated answering,

00:00:07.440 --> 00:00:12.040
hated receiving, hated being asked over the last year,

00:00:12.040 --> 00:00:13.440
that question is this.

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:20.600
What is your AI strategy?

00:00:20.600 --> 00:00:24.959
And let me ask how many of you have been asked this question

00:00:24.959 --> 00:00:28.600
or some variation of this question by upper management,

00:00:28.600 --> 00:00:31.520
by your coworkers, maybe by your spouse,

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:34.639
in my case, my 25 year retired father

00:00:34.639 --> 00:00:36.240
asked me this all the time.

00:00:37.639 --> 00:00:38.560
What is your AI strategy?

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:42.759
And because it's because I have a pretty conflicted

00:00:42.759 --> 00:00:44.439
set of feelings about AI.

00:00:44.439 --> 00:00:47.880
And I like to say I've gone through these five stages

00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:50.160
of AI grief, starting with denial

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:52.040
that like artificial intelligence,

00:00:52.040 --> 00:00:55.119
no, these are just stochastic parrots,

00:00:55.119 --> 00:00:57.639
to anger like enough with this hype,

00:00:57.639 --> 00:00:59.680
like, can we just talk about anything else

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:02.799
but AI these days, to bargaining,

00:01:02.799 --> 00:01:05.120
like, okay, fine, there's something that's interesting

00:01:05.120 --> 00:01:08.400
that's happening and these tools do have something to them,

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:10.720
but like, do we have to get involved right now?

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:13.279
Can we just sort of wait for the dust to settle a little bit

00:01:13.279 --> 00:01:15.519
to depression and feeling like, oh my gosh,

00:01:15.519 --> 00:01:18.680
these things are just gonna take over my profession,

00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:21.919
my livelihood, my kids' futures,

00:01:21.919 --> 00:01:24.599
everything's gonna be, you know, ruined

00:01:24.599 --> 00:01:28.080
to finally acceptance.

00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:30.360
And this journey from depression to acceptance

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:33.400
really, I think, came at the behest of our users,

00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:35.559
Shiny users who were starting to ask,

00:01:35.559 --> 00:01:38.879
like, I am trying to build things with these LLMs

00:01:38.879 --> 00:01:42.120
and the lack of sort of support from Shiny

00:01:42.120 --> 00:01:44.440
is starting to stand in my way.

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:48.040
So we have approached this problem with Shiny and AI

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:49.680
from two different directions.

00:01:49.680 --> 00:01:53.959
First, what does Shiny have to offer AI researchers?

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:56.480
So if you are someone who has an idea for an AI app,

00:01:56.480 --> 00:01:59.760
is Shiny a good framework for you to use?

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:04.160
And secondly, what does AI have to offer Shiny app authors?

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:06.239
So like a lot of us here at PositConf

00:02:06.239 --> 00:02:08.039
who already have Shiny apps

00:02:08.039 --> 00:02:09.800
or already know how to write Shiny apps,

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:13.839
what interesting, useful, and responsible ways

00:02:13.839 --> 00:02:18.559
might there be to leverage LLMs to make our apps better?

00:02:18.559 --> 00:02:19.800
So let's start with this first one.

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:22.520
What can Shiny do for people who are really into AI?

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:26.479
And this whole talk is going to be very much like,

00:02:26.479 --> 00:02:28.119
these are not final answers.

00:02:28.119 --> 00:02:31.160
We are at the beginning of a very long exploration,

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:33.320
but I wanted to share with you some interesting things

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:35.000
we've already experienced.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:36.520
So this is Tina Huang.

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:40.160
She is a YouTuber that talks about data science.

00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:43.080
And lately, everything that she's talking about is AI.

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:46.119
It's all her viewers want to hear.

00:02:46.119 --> 00:02:47.440
And we've been working with Tina,

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:49.279
and Tina had a conversation with Curtis

00:02:49.279 --> 00:02:51.600
in marketing for Posit.

00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:53.320
And Tina said, hi, Curtis,

00:02:53.320 --> 00:02:57.000
I want to build a video chat assistant using GPT 4.0.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:58.839
This is right when GPT 4.0 was announced

00:02:58.839 --> 00:03:01.279
and OpenAI had this big splashy demo

00:03:01.279 --> 00:03:04.639
that you could FaceTime basically with GPT 4.0.

00:03:04.639 --> 00:03:07.119
So she was like, I want to recreate that in Shiny.

00:03:07.119 --> 00:03:08.160
Can we do that with Shiny?

00:03:08.160 --> 00:03:10.399
And he was like, oh yeah, totally.

00:03:10.399 --> 00:03:12.000
You can totally do that with Shiny.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:13.559
And she said, great.

00:03:13.559 --> 00:03:16.800
Can Winston Chang, Winston Chang right here from my team,

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:18.880
can Winston join my live stream in nine days

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:21.000
and live code one of those for me?

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:22.919
And he was like, oh yeah, sure, no problem.

00:03:22.919 --> 00:03:26.800
So a couple of problems with that.

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:29.639
Number one, GPT 4.0, they did this demo,

00:03:29.639 --> 00:03:32.479
but they did not actually publish the API.

00:03:32.479 --> 00:03:35.199
So GPT 4.0 did not actually have a way

00:03:35.199 --> 00:03:37.080
to ingest video input at the time,

00:03:37.080 --> 00:03:39.320
and still does not several months later.

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:41.520
Secondly, Shiny does not have a way

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:45.000
to accept video input directly from the user.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.399
And third, Winston had just gotten on a plane

00:03:47.399 --> 00:03:48.440
to leave for PyCon.

00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:53.639
So fortunately, this first problem, GPT 4.0,

00:03:53.639 --> 00:03:55.279
it turns out that within a few minutes,

00:03:55.279 --> 00:03:59.479
we'd figured out there's this Rube Goldbergian chain

00:03:59.479 --> 00:04:02.880
of commands that we could use to take a video

00:04:02.880 --> 00:04:06.000
and break it down into something that GPT 4.0 could understand.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:07.960
GPT 4.0 could give us text back, and we

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:09.679
could turn that into speech.

00:04:09.679 --> 00:04:11.639
But that did not solve this problem of,

00:04:11.639 --> 00:04:13.679
how do you get video into this app,

00:04:13.679 --> 00:04:16.519
and how do you get this audio to play back?

00:04:16.519 --> 00:04:18.600
So with nine days, I got to work.

00:04:18.600 --> 00:04:22.720
And about a week later, I created this input video clip

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:26.600
component that is available for both R and for Python,

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:29.760
where you could record a short video clip of yourself.

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:32.399
And secondly, an audio spinner component

00:04:32.399 --> 00:04:38.480
that could play audio and then pulse in time with the signal.

00:04:38.480 --> 00:04:42.119
So the morning of the live stream, I had this working.

00:04:42.119 --> 00:04:43.559
I had this application.

00:04:43.559 --> 00:04:45.880
And if you'll just allow me a quick moment,

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:49.920
I would love to demo it for you.

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:52.480
So I'm going to need your help for this.

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:54.600
And I'm going to need the sound on.

00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:57.679
So I'm going to point the webcam at you all.

00:04:57.679 --> 00:04:59.920
So maybe you guys can wave.

00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:03.119
And I can ask the video assistant,

00:05:03.119 --> 00:05:07.279
what does it look like I'm doing right now?

00:05:07.279 --> 00:05:11.880
So it's going to send that input to GPT 4.0.

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:12.839
And I'll get an answer.

00:05:12.839 --> 00:05:14.440
You're speaking to a large audience

00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:16.440
and maybe taking a selfie video.

00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:20.720
The crowd behind you seems engaged, waving, and smiling.

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:21.839
Seems like a fun event.

00:05:25.839 --> 00:05:26.320
Hey.

00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:32.399
Thanks.

00:05:32.399 --> 00:05:34.160
So this is the morning of the live stream,

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:36.239
eight hours before we go live.

00:05:36.239 --> 00:05:38.679
And her response to this was like, OK, that's great.

00:05:38.679 --> 00:05:40.880
What if it could query three different LLMs

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:42.679
and let you compare which one did the best

00:05:42.679 --> 00:05:46.200
and plot which model is in the lead, which

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:51.760
I had some feelings about, but never

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:54.160
want to back down from a shiny challenge.

00:05:54.160 --> 00:05:55.839
I was like, sure, let's give it a try.

00:05:55.839 --> 00:05:58.839
And it turns out that it was not even really that hard.

00:05:58.839 --> 00:06:00.880
And three hours later, I was able to build

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:02.720
this much more complicated version of the app

00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:05.040
that you record a prompt in a similar way,

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:08.079
and it simultaneously does three queries.

00:06:08.079 --> 00:06:11.000
And then you can play them each at a time

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:12.959
and then vote for which one you like the best.

00:06:12.959 --> 00:06:16.160
So less than three hours to do that.

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:19.000
And what I learned from that experience

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:20.920
is that this interactivity in the small,

00:06:20.920 --> 00:06:22.640
making these small, very polished,

00:06:22.640 --> 00:06:24.440
interactive components is hard.

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:27.160
And it does require a lot of web development expertise.

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:30.119
So it took me the better part of this week

00:06:30.119 --> 00:06:33.320
and many years of web development experience

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:35.679
to create really good versions of these components.

00:06:35.679 --> 00:06:38.799
But once those components exist, this interactivity

00:06:38.799 --> 00:06:41.119
in the large, how we connect these components

00:06:41.119 --> 00:06:44.239
in a reactive way, is what Shiny has always

00:06:44.239 --> 00:06:47.239
been designed to do quickly and iteratively.

00:06:47.239 --> 00:06:49.559
So building apps, different kinds

00:06:49.559 --> 00:06:53.000
of apps around these components is super fast and easy.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.679
So for those reasons, I'm very optimistic about what

00:06:55.679 --> 00:06:58.200
Shiny has to offer people in the future

00:06:58.200 --> 00:06:59.799
as they build these kinds of apps,

00:06:59.799 --> 00:07:03.440
as long as we can provide the right components.

00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:05.000
But I think the more, oh, sorry.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:05.959
And the other thing we learned is

00:07:05.959 --> 00:07:07.279
that sometimes you need a Tina.

00:07:07.279 --> 00:07:09.200
Sometimes you need someone who is not

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:11.799
aware of the limitations of the tools

00:07:11.799 --> 00:07:14.119
to make an audacious ask of you.

00:07:14.119 --> 00:07:16.200
And some of our best work happens

00:07:16.200 --> 00:07:20.959
when we have someone making those kinds of audacious asks.

00:07:20.959 --> 00:07:22.920
But the more interesting conversation, I think,

00:07:22.920 --> 00:07:24.480
is around this today.

00:07:24.480 --> 00:07:26.359
What can AI do for Shiny?

00:07:26.359 --> 00:07:28.920
And again, in the spirit of humility,

00:07:28.920 --> 00:07:31.320
I'm just sharing what we have discovered so far.

00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:35.600
But I'm sure we will have a lot of different new things

00:07:35.600 --> 00:07:37.600
are just around the corner besides this.

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:41.119
But I'm really excited to share with you today.

00:07:41.119 --> 00:07:42.959
Actually, the genesis for this demo

00:07:42.959 --> 00:07:44.279
was a conversation with Hadley.

00:07:44.279 --> 00:07:46.119
He said, have you thought at all about how

00:07:46.119 --> 00:07:48.600
you might combine Shiny plus LLMs

00:07:48.600 --> 00:07:51.640
to create dashboards that give the viewer some ability

00:07:51.640 --> 00:07:54.440
to do independent analysis?

00:07:54.440 --> 00:08:02.320
To which I responded, so we took this dashboard

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:07.359
that is one of our most basic templates for Shiny from Python.

00:08:07.359 --> 00:08:12.279
And Carson Sievert here had just created a chat component

00:08:12.279 --> 00:08:15.079
that just shipped with Shiny for Python 1.0 a couple of weeks

00:08:15.079 --> 00:08:15.679
ago.

00:08:15.679 --> 00:08:17.279
So of course, what do we do?

00:08:17.279 --> 00:08:18.320
We put a chat bot on it.

00:08:24.679 --> 00:08:26.079
I'm going to do this live.

00:08:26.079 --> 00:08:26.600
Screw it.

00:08:26.600 --> 00:08:34.200
So can you guys see that OK in the back?

00:08:34.200 --> 00:08:37.599
So we have replaced the sidebar with this chat bot.

00:08:37.599 --> 00:08:39.559
And by the way, I've made the text very big

00:08:39.559 --> 00:08:40.840
for the purposes of this demo.

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:43.200
It's not all out of proportion if you use it for real.

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:44.880
So this is just for today.

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:47.640
So I can ask it simple filtering and sorting things.

00:08:47.640 --> 00:08:51.799
So I can say, show only Sunday dinners.

00:08:51.799 --> 00:08:56.479
So this is showing restaurant tipping data.

00:08:56.479 --> 00:08:58.640
So I ask it to show only dinners, and it says, great.

00:08:58.640 --> 00:09:01.200
I filtered the dashboard to show only Sunday dinners.

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:03.719
And all the plots and things on the right have updated.

00:09:03.719 --> 00:09:06.640
But the key thing here is that it's showing me

00:09:06.640 --> 00:09:08.960
how it did that with SQL.

00:09:08.960 --> 00:09:13.000
And in fact, the way this dashboard works,

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:16.679
this chat bot does not have access to the data.

00:09:16.679 --> 00:09:19.960
In fact, all it has access to is the data schema.

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:22.119
And it knows that this is running DuckDB.

00:09:22.119 --> 00:09:23.640
So if you're going to write SQL, you

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:26.159
should write it in the DuckDB dialect.

00:09:26.159 --> 00:09:30.760
So I don't have to worry about all of these visualizations

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:33.679
being hallucinated or inaccurate.

00:09:33.679 --> 00:09:37.880
The only power that this chat bot has over this dashboard

00:09:37.880 --> 00:09:41.119
is what is the SQL query that it wrote.

00:09:41.119 --> 00:09:43.760
So this is a pretty simple query.

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:45.840
So I can read it and ensure that it did not

00:09:45.840 --> 00:09:46.719
hallucinate anything.

00:09:46.719 --> 00:09:48.080
Yep, that seems fine.

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:51.640
So let me change that now and say, actually,

00:09:51.640 --> 00:09:53.679
invert that filter.

00:09:53.679 --> 00:09:54.479
So do the opposite.

00:09:54.479 --> 00:09:55.840
Instead of only Sunday dinners, it's

00:09:55.840 --> 00:09:58.200
everything but Sunday dinners.

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:00.840
Now, that first example of only show Sunday dinners,

00:10:00.840 --> 00:10:04.159
that's a pretty simple thing to do with Shiny inputs, right?

00:10:04.159 --> 00:10:08.080
You check Sunday, check dinners, and they're ANDed together.

00:10:08.080 --> 00:10:10.200
But this, I mean, it's subtle.

00:10:10.200 --> 00:10:12.080
But saying the inverse of something

00:10:12.080 --> 00:10:14.599
is actually much harder to do with your traditional,

00:10:14.599 --> 00:10:16.239
not just Shiny, but any BI dashboard.

00:10:16.239 --> 00:10:17.840
It's a more complicated thing.

00:10:17.840 --> 00:10:21.280
And let's take it a step further by saying,

00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:23.400
also filter out smokers.

00:10:26.919 --> 00:10:28.479
And now we've ended up with something

00:10:28.479 --> 00:10:31.320
that is like a more complicated Boolean expression.

00:10:31.320 --> 00:10:33.280
And there are very few Shiny apps, indeed,

00:10:33.280 --> 00:10:37.760
that bother to do Boolean combinations of query

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:39.359
parameters.

00:10:39.359 --> 00:10:42.359
So this particular app, let me go ahead and reset

00:10:42.359 --> 00:10:43.520
those filters.

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:47.599
This particular app also has the ability to not only filter,

00:10:47.599 --> 00:10:50.239
but also to answer data questions.

00:10:50.239 --> 00:10:53.799
So I can say, this dashboard is showing the average tip

00:10:53.799 --> 00:10:55.119
and the average bill.

00:10:55.119 --> 00:10:58.440
But it does not show, for example,

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:00.479
what is the average party size.

00:11:04.479 --> 00:11:06.440
So again, it uses SQL.

00:11:06.440 --> 00:11:08.919
It's the only access that it has is writing SQL.

00:11:08.919 --> 00:11:11.239
And for the purposes of answering questions,

00:11:11.239 --> 00:11:15.239
I do permit it to receive the results of that query.

00:11:15.239 --> 00:11:19.320
So it said the average party size is approximately 2.57.

00:11:19.320 --> 00:11:21.239
So let me ask a more interesting question, maybe

00:11:21.239 --> 00:11:22.919
a more controversial question.

00:11:22.919 --> 00:11:25.359
Who tips more, male or female?

00:11:30.200 --> 00:11:31.960
OK, to my surprise, it says males

00:11:31.960 --> 00:11:36.119
tip more, 3.09 versus 2.83.

00:11:36.119 --> 00:11:38.119
And there's a SQL query.

00:11:38.119 --> 00:11:40.440
Does this, I think, strike anyone

00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:43.400
about this answer and the way it came up with the answer?

00:11:46.239 --> 00:11:47.919
We're talking about tipping data.

00:11:47.919 --> 00:11:50.640
And to me, that means what percent did you tip?

00:11:50.640 --> 00:11:53.840
But this has answered in terms of absolute numbers.

00:11:53.840 --> 00:11:58.599
So if I ask it, like, wait, is that absolute or relative

00:11:58.599 --> 00:12:03.119
to total bill?

00:12:03.119 --> 00:12:05.200
And it says, oh, that was absolute.

00:12:05.200 --> 00:12:07.159
Let's go ahead and do the other way.

00:12:07.159 --> 00:12:09.400
And it flips.

00:12:09.400 --> 00:12:13.960
So females actually tip more as a percentage.

00:12:13.960 --> 00:12:16.479
And I can take this further and say, like,

00:12:16.479 --> 00:12:21.119
break that down by day and time.

00:12:27.039 --> 00:12:33.200
And now I get a whole table of different percentages.

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:38.840
Now, this is all stuff that I expected this to be able to do.

00:12:38.840 --> 00:12:41.280
And one interesting thing about working with LLMs

00:12:41.280 --> 00:12:44.320
is how often we find that the thing that we just built

00:12:44.320 --> 00:12:47.119
does things that we did not expect it to be able to do.

00:12:47.119 --> 00:12:50.799
So the first time I was demoing this for someone, I said,

00:12:50.799 --> 00:12:52.039
well, it's only SQL.

00:12:52.039 --> 00:12:53.880
So there's lots that it can't do.

00:12:53.880 --> 00:12:57.200
Like, for example, I can't say, like, filter out

00:12:57.200 --> 00:12:59.919
outliers on total bill.

00:12:59.919 --> 00:13:02.119
Right.

00:13:02.119 --> 00:13:02.840
Oh, OK.

00:13:02.840 --> 00:13:05.320
It's going to take IQR times 1.5.

00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:09.559
And it's going to filter out the outliers, apparently.

00:13:10.559 --> 00:13:14.200
And it filtered out nine outliers.

00:13:14.200 --> 00:13:14.719
OK.

00:13:14.719 --> 00:13:17.719
I guess SQL can do that.

00:13:17.719 --> 00:13:21.919
But maybe that's not how I want it to find outliers.

00:13:21.919 --> 00:13:26.719
I want it to say, like, no, use standard div times 3

00:13:26.719 --> 00:13:27.520
as the definition.

00:13:27.520 --> 00:13:28.640
It's like, OK, sure, great.

00:13:28.640 --> 00:13:30.520
We'll do that instead.

00:13:30.520 --> 00:13:33.599
And not only can we do this filtering out of outliers,

00:13:33.599 --> 00:13:37.080
but we can say, flip that.

00:13:38.080 --> 00:13:39.400
Flip that.

00:13:39.400 --> 00:13:42.239
Show the outliers only.

00:13:45.799 --> 00:13:50.039
And we can see that using this standard deviation times 3,

00:13:50.039 --> 00:13:55.520
these are the four data points that got excluded.

00:13:55.520 --> 00:13:56.760
OK.

00:13:59.039 --> 00:14:00.960
Now, one more feature that I want to show

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:03.599
you before moving on.

00:14:03.640 --> 00:14:08.760
So we are still showing this data with outliers excluded.

00:14:08.760 --> 00:14:11.960
One other feature that we added is the ability

00:14:11.960 --> 00:14:13.400
to explain plots.

00:14:13.400 --> 00:14:16.400
So these are both Plotly plots, but this also

00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:20.080
works with ggplot2 or baseplots or matplotlib

00:14:20.080 --> 00:14:21.719
if you're in Python.

00:14:21.719 --> 00:14:25.440
We added this button to explain what you're seeing here.

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:27.799
And the reason is because sometimes what's

00:14:27.799 --> 00:14:29.840
the right visualization to people,

00:14:29.840 --> 00:14:31.760
like the people at this conference,

00:14:31.760 --> 00:14:34.640
might not be the most understandable thing

00:14:34.640 --> 00:14:37.840
to the decision makers that these dashboards are intended

00:14:37.840 --> 00:14:38.640
for.

00:14:38.640 --> 00:14:43.119
So to remove any possibility of people

00:14:43.119 --> 00:14:45.479
being stuck not knowing what they're looking at,

00:14:45.479 --> 00:14:48.520
we can add this button where it takes a higher resolution

00:14:48.520 --> 00:14:50.880
screenshot of that visualization and then

00:14:50.880 --> 00:14:54.440
asks the chatbot to explain what it sees,

00:14:54.440 --> 00:14:55.840
what observations it can make.

00:14:55.840 --> 00:14:59.479
In this case, it's noticing that there's a positive correlation,

00:14:59.479 --> 00:15:01.280
that there are different things that

00:15:01.280 --> 00:15:04.280
happen below $10 and above $30.

00:15:04.280 --> 00:15:08.479
And by the way, it also notices that this particular

00:15:08.479 --> 00:15:13.599
visualization is based on outliers already being excluded.

00:15:13.599 --> 00:15:16.520
So it is aware of the manipulations

00:15:16.520 --> 00:15:18.359
that we've been doing in the sidebar.

00:15:18.359 --> 00:15:21.960
And you can ask follow-up questions as well down below.

00:15:21.960 --> 00:15:33.479
OK, so what did we learn?

00:15:33.479 --> 00:15:35.919
What did we learn from this experience,

00:15:35.919 --> 00:15:37.239
from this experiment?

00:15:37.239 --> 00:15:39.440
And the biggest takeaway for me was

00:15:39.440 --> 00:15:42.359
the power of domain-specific languages.

00:15:42.359 --> 00:15:46.280
Using SQL as this sort of intermediary

00:15:46.280 --> 00:15:50.679
between the chatbot, the human, and the data app

00:15:50.679 --> 00:15:54.159
worked out fantastically, because SQL

00:15:54.159 --> 00:15:57.039
is pretty easy for LLMs to write these days, at least

00:15:57.039 --> 00:15:59.719
the really frontier models.

00:15:59.719 --> 00:16:03.000
And it's relatively easy for humans to read and reason

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:03.479
about.

00:16:03.479 --> 00:16:05.039
I mean, I don't do a lot of SQL.

00:16:05.039 --> 00:16:07.799
And I write Python and R code every single day.

00:16:07.799 --> 00:16:10.280
But I would rather be debugging those SQL statements

00:16:10.280 --> 00:16:14.239
than debugging a bunch of pandas code,

00:16:14.239 --> 00:16:16.200
or well, dplyr is pretty good.

00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:19.960
But in general, it just constrains

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:22.239
what's possible to express in a way that makes it

00:16:22.239 --> 00:16:25.000
easy to read and reason about.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:27.080
And it's super powerful and flexible.

00:16:27.080 --> 00:16:29.640
Like, with just SQL, we were able to do all those things

00:16:29.640 --> 00:16:33.599
that you saw in this demo.

00:16:33.599 --> 00:16:37.719
And compared to executing straight Python or R that's

00:16:37.719 --> 00:16:41.239
being written by an LLM based on a prompt

00:16:41.239 --> 00:16:45.200
from a possibly malicious user and then executed on my server,

00:16:45.200 --> 00:16:48.799
yeah, I'd rather stick to SQL.

00:16:48.799 --> 00:16:52.000
And this experiment was using SQL.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:56.200
But I'm really excited to experiment further with maybe

00:16:56.200 --> 00:17:00.599
we can use Vega-Lite as a DSL for creating visualizations,

00:17:00.599 --> 00:17:04.079
or use CSS Grid as a DSL for doing different kinds

00:17:04.079 --> 00:17:04.959
of dashboard layouts.

00:17:04.959 --> 00:17:07.599
So you could ask questions in the future like,

00:17:07.599 --> 00:17:09.400
please draw me a scatterplot.

00:17:09.400 --> 00:17:13.520
And instead of getting a bunch of Python or R,

00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:16.000
you get, again, something that's easy for you

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:17.839
to read and reason about.

00:17:20.479 --> 00:17:24.439
And more generally, I was really astounded at what

00:17:24.439 --> 00:17:28.119
I learned once I started coding against these tools.

00:17:28.119 --> 00:17:32.719
So I'm convinced that if your only experience with LLMs

00:17:32.719 --> 00:17:36.520
has been as a consumer of Copilot and ChatGPT,

00:17:36.520 --> 00:17:39.880
that you are actually not well equipped

00:17:39.880 --> 00:17:43.199
to have an informed opinion about what these things can do.

00:17:43.199 --> 00:17:45.520
So a lot of people that I've talked to

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:47.239
have been very skeptical of these tools

00:17:47.239 --> 00:17:48.560
based on their experiences.

00:17:48.560 --> 00:17:51.000
And let me tell you that if that's you,

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:52.800
I really suggest you start coding

00:17:52.800 --> 00:17:56.800
and see what these things can do when you call them with code.

00:17:56.800 --> 00:17:59.079
Secondly, I think it is really time for a lot of us

00:17:59.079 --> 00:18:00.479
who have been skeptical in the past

00:18:00.479 --> 00:18:03.479
to revise our mental model of what these LLMs are

00:18:03.479 --> 00:18:04.920
and what they can do.

00:18:04.920 --> 00:18:08.560
I mean, this stochastic parrot mental model,

00:18:08.560 --> 00:18:10.319
it is true, it is factually true

00:18:10.319 --> 00:18:12.040
that it's an accurate description of them.

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:14.640
It's a very reassuring view of the world

00:18:14.640 --> 00:18:18.439
that these apparently smart things are just stochastic parrots.

00:18:18.439 --> 00:18:20.959
It is an incredibly unhelpful mental model

00:18:20.959 --> 00:18:22.599
if you're thinking about what these things are

00:18:22.599 --> 00:18:23.839
and are not capable of.

00:18:23.839 --> 00:18:26.760
Whereas thinking of them as machines that reason,

00:18:26.760 --> 00:18:28.680
I mean, that is factually false.

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:31.319
It leads us to a fairly terrifying future.

00:18:31.319 --> 00:18:33.439
And also it is a really helpful mental model

00:18:33.439 --> 00:18:34.280
when you're thinking about

00:18:34.280 --> 00:18:36.079
what the potential of these things are.

00:18:37.400 --> 00:18:40.119
Finally, I really want to encourage everybody

00:18:40.119 --> 00:18:42.680
who's hearing this, stay skeptical.

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:45.640
That is one of our superpowers is critical thinking,

00:18:45.640 --> 00:18:47.640
stay skeptical of all the hype,

00:18:47.640 --> 00:18:50.040
but do not let that skepticism

00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:52.199
get in the way of being curious

00:18:52.199 --> 00:18:54.920
about what the potential of these things are,

00:18:54.920 --> 00:18:56.599
not just in the obvious use cases,

00:18:56.599 --> 00:18:59.160
but what non-obvious use cases might there be

00:18:59.160 --> 00:19:00.400
that are right under our noses

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:02.119
that can really make life better for ourselves

00:19:02.119 --> 00:19:03.199
and for our users.

00:19:04.719 --> 00:19:06.199
And if you can do those three things,

00:19:06.199 --> 00:19:09.520
if you can stop just being a consumer and start coding,

00:19:09.520 --> 00:19:11.199
if you can update your mental models

00:19:11.199 --> 00:19:13.359
of what these things might be capable of,

00:19:13.359 --> 00:19:15.880
and if you can let yourself be curious

00:19:15.880 --> 00:19:18.319
about what the potential is here,

00:19:18.319 --> 00:19:22.839
then a year from now, when I see you at PositConf 2025,

00:19:22.839 --> 00:19:24.719
when I ask you this question,

00:19:24.719 --> 00:19:26.520
you'll be ready to answer,

00:19:26.520 --> 00:19:28.599
what is your AI strategy?

00:19:29.880 --> 00:19:30.719
Thank you.

00:19:30.839 --> 00:19:31.680
Thank you.

00:19:31.680 --> 00:19:32.520
Thank you.

